{
  "text": "In our previous discussion and with reference to Fig. 6 we established that if the qubit is projected to |g or |e then the dynamics of the expectation values of the oscillator become either periodic or chaotic-like respectivly. In Fig. 9(b) we plot q as a function of time and by comparison with Fig. 9(a) we observe that the same behaviour is still manifest despite the introduction of \u03c3 x /2 into the Hamiltonian. That is, the oscillator closely monitors the state of the qubit, exhibiting periodic or chaotic-like oscillations when the qubit is in, or near to, |g or |e respectively. We know from our analysis of the master equation, that this is not a \"good\" measurement within the Born framework. Nevertheless, the classical like dynamics of the oscillator provide a clear record of the state of the qubit. In this sense we could consider that effective measurements are still being made. In addition, as we are generating a classical like continuous monitor of the quantum state of the qubit it may well be that quantum circuits constructed in this way may find utility in quantum feedback and control problems (see, for example, [CITATION_1] ).",
